TY  - JOUR
T1  - Occupational Matching: A Test of Sorts
AU  - McCall, Brian P.
Y1  - 1990/02/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261668
DO  - 10.1086/261668
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 45
EP  - 69
VL  - 98
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper develops a theory of job matching in which matching information has both job-specific and occupation-specific components. If occupational matching is significant, then the theory predicts that for those who have switched jobs but remained in the same occupation, increased tenure in the previous job lowers the likelihood of separation from the current job. These predictions are tested using job tenure data from the National Longitudinal Survey's youth cohort. In general, the data are consistent with the occupational matching hypothesis.
AB  - This paper develops a theory of job matching in which matching information has both job-specific and occupation-specific components. If occupational matching is significant, then the theory predicts that for those who have switched jobs but remained in the same occupation, increased tenure in the previous job lowers the likelihood of separation from the current job. These predictions are tested using job tenure data from the National Longitudinal Survey's youth cohort. In general, the data are consistent with the occupational matching hypothesis.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261668
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261668
Y2  - 2024/03/23
